pullRequest.body:
Define the analogous secant-and-tangent negation `neg` and addition `add` on `PointRep` over `F`, and lift them to `PointClass`. Define `Point` as a `PointClass` that is nonsingular. Prove in `neg_equiv` and `add_equiv` that these operations preserve the equivalence. Prove in `nonsingular_neg` and `nonsingular_add` that these operations preserve nonsingularity by reducing it to the affine case, and lift these proofs to `PointClass`.

This is the third in a series of four PRs leading to #9405 and is analogous to #9418

This could be `(P x * Q z) â€¢ ` if you generalize the scalar multiplication.

As I said [here](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9405#issuecomment-2141231117) I think it's reasonable to generalize the scalar multiplication to get rid of Units.mk0. This division in `Units F` could be replaced with division in the field F.

Restricting to scalar multiplication by units forces you to state less general results, which I think is bad.
Oh I'm totally for this, I just wasn't sure before whether I should combine the changes with this PR, but I guess I will.

I have extended the scalar multiplication to include non-units in the latest commit, but I think that the equivalence relation must still be on the units e.g. to prove `nonsingular_smul`, so much of the code will now require `IsUnit u`. Overall this increases the code length, because now we have to add the `IsUnit` lemmas, but I think once we refactor `Nonsingular` into the correct definition over a larger class of rings e.g. valuation rings, this will save us some work.

Thanks! Yes the equivalence relation needs a **group** action, and only units have inverses.

It seems my suggestion to replace the `Units.mk0` is what makes the code longer, which I regret. By using `Units.mk0` you essentially bundled the nonzero proof inside the statement of the lemma, so you no longer need the nonzero proofs when applying the lemma. Since these lemmas seem to be auxiliary and applied at multiple occasions, it may be wise to keep the original `Units.mk0` statement, and only generalize selected lemmas like in [my branch](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/compare/EllipticCurve.Jacobian...EllipticCurve.Jacobian+) which don't increase code length.

I'm not sure it's very useful to generalize from `ne_zero` to `isUnit` for a larger class of rings, and it may be a tedious task to figure out which results generalize. (It might be more useful in the projective case, we'll see.)
We'll stick with this for now, even if it's longer.
You are missing the condition `P x * Q z ^ 2 = Q x * P z ^ 2` in the docstring.
Thanks.

I [once remarked](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9405#pullrequestreview-2072733853) that this expression appears in `dblX` and `dblY` as well. Since you are now introducing a shorthand for it, maybe use it there as well?
Sure, why not. For now I'll stick with `P y - W.negY P` instead of `eval W polynomialY` since it's shorter, unless this becomes more convenient in the future for any reason.

I've been wondering whether [WeierstrassCurve.Affine.addX](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/AlgebraicGeometry/EllipticCurve/Affine.html#WeierstrassCurve.Affine.addX), addY' and addY should take four arguments x1 x2 y1 y2, with `L = slope W x1 x2 y1 y2` plugged in ... (and it feels to me that the argument order x1 y1 x2 y2 would be better)
Now that we have the projective and Jacobian API, I'm actually inclined to change the affine API to take in tuples `Fin 2 -> R` rather than having an arbitrary order for `x/y1/2` - what do you think?

That could be more convenient, we'll see. I may work on the reduction homomorphism during or before the AIM workshop, in which homogenization is involved. To develop the homogenization API I think it's best to take an Equiv `Î± â‰ƒ Option Î²`, and in this case we can use [finSuccEquiv](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Logic/Equiv/Fin.html#finSuccEquiv).

Have you tried the following method of proof: since we have `nonsingular_smul` and `add_smul_of_(not_)equiv` (homogeneity of `add`), if we change P and Q by scalar multiplication by units, the truth values of hP, hQ and the conclusion will remain unchanged, so we can assume `P` and `Q` are of the form `![X,Y,1]` or `![1,1,0]`. This is the approach taken in my notes, and I think it would reduce the need of lemmas for general triples, and only the lemmas that connect to the affine API would be needed. For example, the lemma `add_of_Y_ne'` could be stated with `Px Py Qx Qy : F` rather than `P Q : Fin 3 â†’ F`. To show the bijection between Jacobian.Point and Affine.Point is a group isomorphism, it also suffices to check one representative for each point class.

Indeed, this was essentially my approach before I rewrote everything (e.g. check the `nonsingular_add` in [this commit](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9435/commits/fa01869a99ed2fbab2a8018d7b90f0b21bff1372)) - basically I reduced the problem to the affine case using `nonsingular_of_equiv` applied to `add_equiv` applied to the affine lemmas (using `nonsingular_smul` instead just means you need one more `add_smul`). Ultimately I think the current approach is more modular, spreading over more lemmas with short proofs, and the code for `nonsingular_add` is much clearer to me. Having lemmas for a general triple would make the general API easier to use anyway, and as I said above I do prefer taking in `Fin 3 -> F` rather than `Px Py Qx Qy`.
Why is it necessary to have a version with the scalar multiplication expanded out?
Because they don't need the assumption that we're working over a field, but I don't know how useful this would be.

But this supposedly also works?
```suggestion
lemma addXYZ_of_Z_eq_zero_left {P Q : Fin 3 â†’ R} (hP : W.Equation P) (hPz : P z = 0) :
    W'.addXYZ P Q = (P x * Q z) â€¢ Q := by
  rw [smul_fin3, addXYZ, addX_of_Z_eq_zero_left hPz, addY_of_Z_eq_zero_left hP hPz, addZ_of_Z_eq_zero_left hPz]
```
I guess it does...
I'm not sure about the necessity of changing `n` to `-n` (seems to make left-to-right rewrite harder), but since this (and another) lemma is private I don't mind.
